  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Without using a computational device, determine the exact value of each of the following quantities.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol marker="a." cols="3">
          <!-- WHY WILL THIS NOT DISPLAY IN TWO COLUMNS?  BIZARRE -->
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\sin(-\frac{11\pi}{4})</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\cos(\frac{29\pi}{6})</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\cos(\frac{17\pi}{3})</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\sin(47\pi)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\cos(-113\pi)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>t</m> in quadrant III such that <m>\cos(t) = -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>t</m> in quadrant IV such that <m>\sin(t) = -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        Exercise Answer
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li><p><m>\sin\!\left(-\frac{11\pi}{4}\right) = \sin\!\left(\frac{5\pi}{4}\right) = -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m></p></li>
          <li><p><m>\cos\!\left(\frac{29\pi}{6}\right) = \cos\!\left(\frac{5\pi}{6}\right) = -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m></p></li>
          <li><p><m>\cos\!\left(\frac{17\pi}{3}\right) = \cos\!\left(\frac{5\pi}{3}\right) = \frac{1}{2}</m></p></li>
          <li><p><m>\sin(47\pi) = 0</m></p></li>
          <li><p><m>\cos(-113\pi) = \cos(113\pi) = (-1)^{113} = -1</m></p></li>
          <li><p><m>t = \frac{7\pi}{6}</m></p></li>
          <li><p><m>t = \frac{5\pi}{3}</m></p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        We now know three different identities involving the sine and cosine functions: <m>\sin(t+\frac{\pi}{2}) = \cos(t)</m>, <m>\cos(t-\frac{\pi}{2}) = \sin(t)</m>, and <m>\cos^2(t) + \sin^2(t) = 1</m>.  Following are several proposed identities.  For each, your task is to decide whether the identity is true or false.  If true, give a convincing argument for why it is true; if false, give an example of a <m>t</m>-value for which the equation fails to hold.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol marker="a." cols="2">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\cos(t + 2\pi) = \cos(t)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\sin(t-\pi) = -\sin(t)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\cos(t - \frac{3\pi}{2}) = \sin(t)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\sin^2(t) = 1 - \cos^2(t)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\sin(t) + \cos(t) = 1</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\sin(t) + \sin(\frac{\pi}{2}) = \cos(t)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>

    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        Exercise Answer
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <ol marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              Yes, <m>\cos(t+2\pi) = \cos(t)</m> is true because the function has a periodicity of <m>2\pi</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Yes, <m>\sin(t-\pi) = -\sin(t)</m> is true because a shift of <m>\pi</m> around the unit circle is equivalent to making the argument negative, and <m>\sin</m> is an odd function.  Also, graphically, <m>\sin</m> gives the <m>y</m>-coordinate of points on the unit circle, and shifting the argument by <m>\pm\pi</m> essentially reflects the point across the <m>x</m>-axis, changing the sign of the <m>y</m>-coordinate.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              No, <m>\cos\!\left(t - \frac{3\pi}{2}\right) \ne \sin(t)</m>.  For example, <m>\cos\!\left(\frac{\pi}{2} - \frac{3\pi}{2}\right) = \cos(-\pi) = -1</m> while <m>\sin\!\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) = 1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Yes, <m>\sin^2(t) = 1 - \cos^2(t)</m>, because of the Fundamental Trigonometric Identity.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              No, <m>\sin(t) + \cos(t) \ne 1</m>.  For example, <m>\sin\!\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) + \cos\!\left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) = \frac{1 + \sqrt{3}}{2} \ne 1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              No, <m>\sin(t) + \sin\!\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) \ne \cos(t)</m>.  For example, <m>\sin\!\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) + \sin\!\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) = \frac{\sqrt{2} + 2}{2}</m> while <m>\cos\!\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

